│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion failure in                │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup, which verifies that any instruction being       │
│ removed (an instruction inserted during SCEV expansion) is only used by other │
│ inserted instructions. This typically indicates that cleanup is trying to     │
│ erase an SCEV-inserted instruction that still has a non-inserted user.\n\nIn  │
│ LoopVectorize, GeneratedRTChecks builds SCEV-based checks and memory runtime  │
│ checks in temporary blocks. If these checks are not emitted (i.e., unused),   │
│ the destructor is supposed to clean them up. For MemCheckBlock, there's a     │
│ specific pre-cleanup step that erases non-inserted instructions that may use  │
│ expanded values. For SCEVCheckBlock, there is no analogous pre-cleanup step,  │
│ so non-inserted instructions can still be users of inserted ones, triggering  │
│ the assertion during SCEV cleanup.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe backtrace  │
│ shows the assertion in SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup called from               │
│ GeneratedRTChecks::~GeneratedRTChecks. No other debug logs were available,    │
│ but the location pinpoints the first transformation at cleanup, indicating    │
│ the inconsistency occurs during removal of expanded instructions associated   │
│ with SCEV checks.\n\n3. Root Cause                                            │
│ Analysis:\nGeneratedRTChecks::~GeneratedRTChecks currently pre-cleans         │
│ MemCheckBlock by erasing non-inserted instructions (which may be              │
│ compares/branches using SCEV-generated values) before invoking the            │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaners. However, it does not perform an equivalent step for     │
│ SCEVCheckBlock. When SCEVCheckCond is present (meaning the SCEV checks were   │
│ built but not emitted), SCEVCheckBlock may still contain non-inserted         │
│ instructions that use inserted ones. SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup then        │
│ attempts to remove inserted instructions, but finds non-inserted users,       │
│ violating the assertion.\n\nThe reproducer has a value %iv.1 defined in       │
│ loop.1 used in trip count for loop.2, which makes SCEV generate checks        │
│ involving cross-loop values, leading to the SCEVCheckBlock containing mixed   │
│ inserted and non-inserted instructions. Without the pre-cleanup, the          │
│ assertion triggers.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nAdd a pre-cleanup block in │
│ GeneratedRTChecks::~GeneratedRTChecks() analogous to the MemRuntimeCheckCond  │
│ case, but for SCEV checks. Specifically, before calling                       │
│ SCEVCleaner.cleanup(), when SCEVCheckCond is still set (i.e., checks not      │
│ emitted), erase non-inserted instructions from SCEVCheckBlock and make        │
│ ScalarEvolution forget them.\n\nEdit location:                                │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp lines 2065-2084.\n\nProposed  │
│ patch (conceptually):\n- Insert the following after setting markResultUsed    │
│ logic and before calling MemCheckCleaner.cleanup() and                        │
│ SCEVCleaner.cleanup():\n\n  if (SCEVCheckCond) {\n    auto &SE =              │
│ *SCEVExp.getSE();\n    for (auto &I :                                         │
│ make_early_inc_range(reverse(*SCEVCheckBlock))) {\n      if                   │
│ (SCEVExp.isInsertedInstruction(&I))\n        continue;\n                      │
│ SE.forgetValue(&I);\n      I.eraseFromParent();\n    }\n  }\n\nThis mirrors   │
│ the MemRuntimeCheck pre-cleanup and ensures that all non-inserted             │
│ instructions using inserted SCEV values are removed before                    │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner runs, satisfying the assertion that inserted instructions │
│ have only inserted users.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to missing      │
│ pre-cleanup for SCEVCheckBlock in GeneratedRTChecks destructor when SCEV      │
│ checks are not emitted. By erasing non-inserted instructions in               │
│ SCEVCheckBlock prior to calling SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup, we restore the  │
│ invariant required by the cleanup routine and prevent the assertion failure.  │
│ This change aligns SCEV checks handling with the existing MemCheck handling   │
│ and should fix the reported crash while preserving LCSSA form and ensuring    │
│ consistent cleanup behavior."})                                               │
