│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash is an assertion failure in SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup, which      │
│ verifies that any instruction being removed (an instruction inserted during   │
│ SCEV expansion) is only used by other inserted instructions. This typically   │
│ indicates that cleanup is trying to erase an SCEV-inserted instruction that   │
│ still has a non-inserted user.                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ In LoopVectorize, GeneratedRTChecks builds SCEV-based checks and memory       │
│ runtime checks in temporary blocks. If these checks are not emitted (i.e.,    │
│ unused), the destructor is supposed to clean them up. For MemCheckBlock,      │
│ there's a specific pre-cleanup step that erases non-inserted instructions     │
│ that may use expanded values. For SCEVCheckBlock, there is no analogous       │
│ pre-cleanup step, so non-inserted instructions can still be users of inserted │
│ ones, triggering the assertion during SCEV cleanup.                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The backtrace shows the assertion in SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup called from │
│ GeneratedRTChecks::~GeneratedRTChecks. No other debug logs were available,    │
│ but the location pinpoints the first transformation at cleanup, indicating    │
│ the inconsistency occurs during removal of expanded instructions associated   │
│ with SCEV checks.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ GeneratedRTChecks::~GeneratedRTChecks currently pre-cleans MemCheckBlock by   │
│ erasing non-inserted instructions (which may be compares/branches using       │
│ SCEV-generated values) before invoking the SCEVExpanderCleaners. However, it  │
│ does not perform an equivalent step for SCEVCheckBlock. When SCEVCheckCond is │
│ present (meaning the SCEV checks were built but not emitted), SCEVCheckBlock  │
│ may still contain non-inserted instructions that use inserted ones.           │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup then attempts to remove inserted instructions,   │
│ but finds non-inserted users, violating the assertion.                        │
│                                                                               │
│ The reproducer has a value %iv.1 defined in loop.1 used in trip count for     │
│ loop.2, which makes SCEV generate checks involving cross-loop values, leading │
│ to the SCEVCheckBlock containing mixed inserted and non-inserted              │
│ instructions. Without the pre-cleanup, the assertion triggers.                │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Add a pre-cleanup block in GeneratedRTChecks::~GeneratedRTChecks() analogous  │
│ to the MemRuntimeCheckCond case, but for SCEV checks. Specifically, before    │
│ calling SCEVCleaner.cleanup(), when SCEVCheckCond is still set (i.e., checks  │
│ not emitted), erase non-inserted instructions from SCEVCheckBlock and make    │
│ ScalarEvolution forget them.                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit location: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp lines          │
│ 2065-2084.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Proposed patch (conceptually):                                                │
│ - Insert the following after setting markResultUsed logic and before calling  │
│ MemCheckCleaner.cleanup() and SCEVCleaner.cleanup():                          │
│                                                                               │
│   if (SCEVCheckCond) {                                                        │
│     auto &SE = *SCEVExp.getSE();                                              │
│     for (auto &I : make_early_inc_range(reverse(*SCEVCheckBlock))) {          │
│       if (SCEVExp.isInsertedInstruction(&I))                                  │
│         continue;                                                             │
│       SE.forgetValue(&I);                                                     │
│       I.eraseFromParent();                                                    │
│     }                                                                         │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This mirrors the MemRuntimeCheck pre-cleanup and ensures that all             │
│ non-inserted instructions using inserted SCEV values are removed before       │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner runs, satisfying the assertion that inserted instructions │
│ have only inserted users.                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is due to missing pre-cleanup for SCEVCheckBlock in                 │
│ GeneratedRTChecks destructor when SCEV checks are not emitted. By erasing     │
│ non-inserted instructions in SCEVCheckBlock prior to calling                  │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup, we restore the invariant required by the        │
│ cleanup routine and prevent the assertion failure. This change aligns SCEV    │
│ checks handling with the existing MemCheck handling and should fix the        │
│ reported crash while preserving LCSSA form and ensuring consistent cleanup    │
│ behavior.                                                                     │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
